<HL>
   International:
   Two Mitsubishi
   Group Members
   Plan to Reunite
   ---
   Japanese Industrial Combine
   Says Merger in December
   Isn't Monopolistic Threat
   ----
   By Yumiko Ono and Kathryn Graven
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   J.MBM J.MMC WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
NON-FERROUS METALS (ONF)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Two members of the powerful Mitsubishi industrial
group, Mitsubishi Metal Corp. and Mitsubishi Mining &amp; Cement
Co., announced they would reunite in December.
   The two companies had been formed when Mitsubishi Mining
was broken up during the U.S. occupation of Japan after World
War II. Officials, announcing the merging of the two
companies, attempted to head off expected criticism that the
move is a step toward re-establishment of the monopoly power
held by Japan's prewar "zaibatsu" financial combines. The
Mitsubishi Group comprised one of the three most powerful
zaibatsu before and during the war.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The new company, which will be named in May, will be
Japan's largest producer of nonferrous metals. On its own,
Mitsubishi Metal ranks as Japan's leading producer of
aluminum cans and is second in the production of silicon
wafers for semiconductors. Mitsubishi Mining &amp; Cement is a
leading producer of building materials.
   The presidents of the two companies said the merger
shouldn't be seen as a monopolistic threat. "We're two
companies in the same group that are merging," said
Mitsubishi Metal President Takeshi Nagano, who will be
chairman of the new company. "We aren't taking in others from
outside the group to get bigger."
   Masaya Fujimura, president of Mitsubishi Mining &amp; Cement,
who will be president of the new company, said the merger
also isn't aimed at strengthening ties within the Mitsubishi
family, which is already known for its strong intragroup
links. Instead, the companies said the merger would help
protect against international currency fluctuations to which
the metals business is vulnerable. And as both companies
strive to diversify into new areas of business, their joint
research capabilities will be strengthened, they said.
   The merger comes as the 160-company Mitsubishi Group is
restructuring in an attempt to become more globally
competitive. For example, Mitsubishi Corp., the trading house
that is one of the group's four core companies, this year
jumped into the international acquisitions fray with a bid
for Aristech Chemical Corp. of Pittsburgh. In March, the
Mitsubishi Group announced exploratory discussions on a range
of ties with West German conglomerate Daimler-Benz AG.
   The merger also comes at a time when the U.S. is examining
business practices that may hamper foreign access to the
Japanese market. In the current "structural impediments"
talks, the U.S. argues that Japan's industrial groups, known
as "keiretsu", effectively work to keep out foreign firms.
   Mr. Nagano tried to calm fears about how the combined firm
would operate in the U.S, where both companies have
operations. "I don't think the U.S. will feel more threatened
about our work after the merger," Mr. Nagano said.
   But analysts said that in a few years, the merged company
may want to expand in the U.S., especially to produce cement.
"We may actually see a day when {the Mitsubishi Group}
transfers its raw-material operations overseas," said Mark
Brown, a construction analyst at Barclays de Zoete Wedd
Securities (Japan) Ltd.
   The two companies are considered second-tier members of
the Mitsubishi Group, whose leading companies are Mitsubishi
Corp., the trading house, Mitsubishi Heavy Industries Ltd.,
Mitsubishi Motors Corp. and Mitsubishi Electric Corp.
   Analysts said the merger makes sense because the two
companies are diversifying in similar directions. As Japan's
mining industry all but died with the upward valuation of the
yen since 1985, Mitsubishi Mining &amp; Cement was forced to move
out of mining and into developing new building materials and
advanced ceramics. The company closed its last coal mine last
month, marking the end of the company's 120-year coal-mining
business.
   Mitsubishi Metal, which concentrates on nonferrous metals,
has also been moving into new products such as processed
metals and electronics materials. Both companies also have
been examining real-estate development projects.
   "Rather than compete against each other," says Ken
Maruyama, a senior analyst at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew
International Ltd., "this merger is the best way to expand
business."
   The companies said this would be a fairly equal merger,
with nine shares of Mitsubishi Metal equaling 10 shares of
Mitsubishi Mining &amp; Cement. Annual sales of the new company
are expected to reach the equivalent of $5.7 billion in the
first year, and $6.4 billion within five years. The new
company, with total assets of $5.1 billion, will employ about
9,000 people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900411-0124
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900411-0124.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology &amp; Health:
   Study Uncovers New Evidence Linking
   Strain on Job and High Blood Pressure
   ----
   By Ron Winslow
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<LP>
   Health researchers have come up with new evidence that
stress on the job may make you sick.
   Men who hold jobs with high demands over which they have
little control are three times more likely to suffer from
high blood pressure than men who don't, the researchers
report. These workers are also more likely to sustain
physical changes to the heart that over time could lead to
heart disease.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The study is the first to link job strain and high blood
pressure, according to Peter L. Schnall, the lead author, who
is assistant professor of medicine at New York
Hospital-Cornell Medical College, New York. While it doesn't
prove that job stress causes high blood pressure, "it opens
the door for trying to understand" the relationship between
the two, and that could have profound consequences for the
work force -- from the factory floor to the executive suite.
   "The study suggests that what's critical is the amount of
control you have when faced with a challenging situation,"
Dr. Schnall says. "If that's correct, one of the things we
could do would be to enhance worker control and participation
on the job."
   Indeed, it suggests that redesigning jobs to relieve
strain could improve the health of a company's work force and
reduce health costs, among other things. Conversely, failing
to mitigate stress's impact could provoke labor problems or
increase workers compensation claims.
   Further study is required, however, before such definitive
conclusions can be made, Dr. Schnall says. The current study
is published in today's Journal of the American Medical
Association.
   Previous studies have linked job strain to coronary heart
disease, Dr. Schnall says. While the relationship between
stress and high blood pressure has long been suspected, it
hasn't been established, in part, the researchers speculate,
because of difficulty in developing reliable means of
determining blood pressure levels and evaluating stress.
   The subjects of the study wore monitors during one 24-hour
period to record blood pressure at 15-minute intervals during
waking hours and every 30 minutes at night. Taking frequent
readings during a person's normal activities yields more
reliable measurements than traditional readings in a clinic,
the researchers said.
   In addition, the study defines job strain in terms of both
psychological demands -- excessive work, conflicting demands,
insufficient time to work -- and worker control and
discretion over job decisions.
   "Telling us you work very fast or hard wasn't associated
with rise of blood pressure," Dr. Schnall says, nor was lack
of job freedom. "Only those folks who told us both things
were happening at the same time were having {blood pressure}
problems," he says.
   The researchers studied 215 men from 30 to 60 years old at
seven worksites in New York City. They ranged from clerical
workers to executives at a newspaper typography department, a
federal health agency, a brokerage house, a private hospital,
a sanitation collection and repair facility and a department
store warehouse. They were selected from 2,556 potential
subjects.
   Of the 215, 87 had diastolic blood pressure -- the lower
pressure, measured between contractions of the heart --
between 85 and 105 and were considered hypertensive. The
other 128 men had normal blood pressure and were considered
controls. Women weren't included in the study because their
response to job strain could be different and the cost of
recruiting enough subjects for reliable data would have been
too high, Dr. Schnall said. The research team is doing
additional studies that include women, he added.
   Among other findings:
   -- Men aged 30 to 40 with high blood pressure had
significantly thicker heart muscle than those in the control
group, an indication of the additional work required of the
heart in hypertensive people. While none were at immediate
risk of heart disease, Dr. Schnall said, thicker than normal
heart muscle is considered an important predictor of heart
disease and thus can lead to later trouble if blood pressure
isn't controlled.
   -- Risk of developing job-related hypertension increases
with age. Men between 51 and 60 in high-strain jobs were 5.2
times more likely to have high blood pressure than those in
the control group, while those between 41 and 50 were two and
a half times as likely to have hypertension.
   -- As expected, age, weight and regular consumption of
alcohol were linked to high blood pressure. Researchers
adjusted their data for these and several other factors in
establishing the correlation between job stress and
hypertension.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900411-0123
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900411-0123.
</DOCID>
