</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Theater: `Aspects of Love'
   ----
   By Edwin Wilson
</HL>
<DATE>
04/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<LP>
   New York -- The trouble with "Aspects of Love" begins in
the very first aria. In the first scene of the musical that
opened recently at the Broadhurst Theater, Alex (Michael
Ball) is standing on the terrace of a country home in
Southwest France. He faces a woman seated at a wooden trestle
table. When he begins to sing softly, it is clear that his
sotto voce rendition would not reach past the second row, but
it booms out over the loudspeaker system through the whole
house. We know right away that voices are going to be
amplified in this production; it turns out everything else is
amplified as well, including the overwrought emotions of the
characters.
   "Aspects of Love" is based on a 1955 novel by David
Garnett, a brief, unpretentious work marked by the subtlety
of the interconnected personal relationships. Composer Andrew
Lloyd Webber must have felt it was the ideal vehicle for him
to move headlong into the adult world.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Until now, Mr. Lloyd Webber has written frequently about
the fantasy world of children in such musicals as "Cats" and
"Starlight Express." Not only that, he has named the many
corporate entities he controls after escapist characters or
concepts from that same world. His best known company -- and
the producer of all his recent musicals, including "Aspects
of Love" -- is the Really Useful Company, named for a train
engine in a children's book.
   In contrast, the novel "Aspects of Love" deals with a
grown-up, sophisticated world of liaisons and affairs. The
story begins in Montpellier in the south of France, where
Alex, a young man, becomes infatuated with an actress, Rose
Vibert (Ann Crumb), who suddenly is out of work for two
weeks. He persuades her to come to Pau in the Pyrenees. His
wealthy uncle has an estate there that he never visits, where
they can live free of charge. Alex's Uncle George (Kevin
Colson), alerted by the caretaker of the estate, unexpectedly
shows up to confront the couple, and soon thereafter Rose
leaves to rejoin her theatrical troupe. Two years pass in
which Alex, now in the army, has been away. He returns to
Paris and on a visit to his uncle discovers that Rose is now
living with Uncle George as his mistress. Insane with
jealousy, Alex pulls out a gun and in the ensuing argument
with Rose, the gun goes off and he grazes her arm with a
bullet.
   Meanwhile, George is attracted to Giulietta (Kathleen Rowe
McAllen), an Italian sculptress. Despite this attachment, he
marries Rose, and we move 13 years ahead to the time when
they have an attractive daughter of 12 and Alex enters their
lives once more. Over the next two years Alex develops a
deep, though platonic relationship, with the daughter, Jenny
(Danielle Du Clos), and she falls childishly but passionately
in love with him. George dies and Alex realizes that he must
end the relationship with Jenny; as the story ends, he has
turned from Jenny and begun an affair with Giulietta.
   Whereas in the Garnett novel these relationships are a
tissue of nuances, told with sensitivity and psychological
insight, in the musical everything is overblown. The scenery
was created by Maria Bjornson, who designed "The Phantom of
the Opera." For the more intimate "Aspects of Love" she has
fashioned large-scale effects out of all proportion to the
story. Two brief scenes -- at a sculpture exhibit in Paris
and in Giulietta's studio in Venice -- become full-stage
settings filled with elaborate, outsize objects: an
old-fashioned phonograph with a woman's legs protruding from
the horn, human heads broken into planes like geological
faults. The main background of the set is the brick wall for
George's villa. At one point, when Alex and Rose are hiking,
the wall breaks apart like a giant cracked egg to show a
panorama of the Pyrenees.
   As with the scenery, the emotional entanglements are
inflated. A one-line reference in the novel to an attraction
between Rose and Giulietta leads to a full-blown lesbian
attachment in the musical. In fact, the moment any two likely
lovers set eyes on each other, the music swells and we know
that "amour" is in the air. So quickly do liaisons develop
and dissolve that the musical often seems like a synopsis of
the story rather than the unfolding of a plot. At times, this
leads to unintentional comedy. The scene, for example, in
which Alex attempts to shoot Rose, abruptly turns from
melodrama to high farce. After the shooting, the maid comes
rushing in with a hammer and strikes at Alex, and though the
blow stops a good six inches from his head, he collapses in a
heap.
   Once George returns and order is restored, the two men in
Rose's life, each of whom has insisted he could not live
without her, suddenly begs the other to take her off his
hands in the duet "She'd Be Better Off With You." The music
follows the same pattern as the other elements in "Aspects of
Love." In the manner of recent British musicals, there is
scoring from beginning to end, so that even mundane phrases
such as "Would you like a cup of coffee?" "No thank you, I
prefer tea" are sung, sometimes with a decidedly droll
effect. The lyrics, by the way, are by Don Black and Charles
Hart.
   When we turn from recitatives to arias, each one without
fail builds to a mighty crescendo at the conclusion, whether
the underlying emotion justifies it or not. Also, because he
does not appear fully to trust individual declarations, Mr.
Lloyd Webber several times introduces a full chorus -- at
George's vineyard and at his funeral. The cast, it should be
noted, handles the music well enough, but meets with varying
degrees of success in conveying any depth of character.
   How do we explain why Mr. Lloyd Webber and his director,
Trevor Nunn, have treated the delicate fabric of "Aspects of
Love" in such grandiose fashion? Any answer obviously would
be speculation, but one possibility is that both men have met
with such success when pulling out all the stops -- Mr. Nunn,
after all, has guided such blockbuster musicals as "Cats" and
"Les Miserables" -- that they have difficulty scaling back
when they come to a far more intimate, personal subject. One
of the big numbers in "Aspects of Love" is "Love Changes
Everything." Well, yes, but when it comes to show business,
apparently not for Messrs. Lloyd Webber and Nunn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900411-0113
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900411-0113.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Stocks End Mixed as Investors Seek
   Bargains or Firms With Strong Net
   ----
   By Craig Torres and David Wilson
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Stocks ended mixed as investors continued to
swap industry groups in a hunt for cheap stocks or companies
with strong earnings.
   Technology stocks gained sharply yesterday following a
strong first-quarter earnings report from Motorola. Airline
and bank issues also attracted buying interest, while energy
stocks headed lower as oil prices continued to fall.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 9.01 to 2731.08.
Broader market measures had more modest gains: Standard &amp;
Poor's 500-Stock Index, for example, gained 0.70, to 342.07,
the equivalent of a five-point increase in the 30-stock
industrial average. Stocks declining on the New York Stock
Exchange outpaced advancers for the fifth-consecutive day by
740 to 723.
   Big Board volume totaled 136,020,000 shares, up from
114,970,000 shares Monday, the second-slowest trading day of
the year.
   Motorola soared 4 1/4 to 68 1/2 on approximately two
million shares after reporting a 3.2% increase in
first-quarter net income from a year earlier.
   John Lazlo, an analyst at PaineWebber, said the stock rose
sharply because many investors were expecting a disappointing
quarter. Though earnings in the company's communications
sector were "below target," Mr. Lazlo said, "semiconductor
revenues grew more than people thought."
   Rajiv Chaudri, an analyst at Goldman Sachs, said he would
boost his estimate of Motorola's full-year earnings to a
range of $4.60 to $4.75 a share from $4.50 a share, based on
the first-quarter report.
   Texas Instruments, another major chip maker, added 2 1/8
to 37 1/2, and computer stocks also recorded solid gains.
International Business Machines rose 3/8 to 105 7/8, Compaq
Computer rose 2 1/8 to 96 1/2, Digital Equipment rose 1 7/8
to 81 7/8 and Hewlett-Packard advanced 1 3/8 to 45 1/8.
   Energy stocks dropped across the board as May crude-oil
futures plunged 76 cents a barrel to $17.68 in New York
trading. Worries about a possible glut had driven the price
of crude down about $1 a barrel last week; the May contract
on West Texas Intermediate crude dropped 71 cents a barrel
Monday.
   Among major oil issues, Exxon remained unchanged at 46,
Texaco eased 5/8 to 58 3/8, Mobil slipped 1/2 to 60 5/8 and
Amoco skidded 1 to 51 3/8. Baker Hughes, which reached an
agreement with the Justice Department that will allow it to
complete a takeover of Norton's oil-services unit, fell 3/4
to 27 1/4; elsewhere in the sector, Rowan dropped 5/8 to 12
1/2 and McDermott International lost 1/2 to 27.
   Bank issues extended their recovery from a sell-off late
last week. Citicorp gained 5/8 to 24 1/4, BankAmerica gained
3/4 to 27 1/8, Chase Manhattan added 5/8 to 28 3/4 and
Manufacturers Hanover rallied 1 1/2 to 33 1/8. Among regional
banks, NCNB rose 1 1/2 to 37 5/8, National City gained 5/8 to
34 1/8, Shawmut National rose 1/2 to 13 1/2 and UJB Financial
added 5/8 to 15 1/8.
   UAL rose 1/4 to 161 1/4 after reaching a definitive
agreement for a buy-out, valued at $200 a share, by the three
principal unions at its United Airlines unit. Other airline
stocks fared much better; AMR, the parent of American
Airlines, climbed 2 to 65 3/8; Delta Air Lines rose 1 1/4 to
72 1/2; USAir Group added 3/4 to 30, and Southwest Airlines
rose 1/2 to 24 1/4.
   Ames Department Stores, the most active Big Board issue,
retreated 7/8 to 2 3/8 on composite volume of 4.8 million
shares in response to news that it plans to close 74 stores
and expects to report a $228 million loss for the fiscal year
ended Jan. 27. The estimated loss was larger than
anticipated.
   TJX, which holds a major stake in Ames as a result of the
company's acquisition of the Zayre discount-store chain in
late 1988, tumbled 1 to 15 1/8 on 2.4 million shares.
   Archer-Daniels-Midland fell 1 to 23 1/8 on 1.4 million
shares. Merrill Lynch and Bear Stearns slightly lowered
earnings estimates for the fiscal third quarter ended in
March. The company indicated to Dow Jones Professional
Investor Report that its net income may be below the
year-earlier 41 cents a share, although its operating
earnings "should be up."
   Jakarta Growth Fund, a new single-country mutual fund
focusing on Indonesia, slipped below its initial offering
price. Five million shares of the closed-end fund were sold
at $12 apiece; the stock closed at 11 7/8 on its first day of
trading, with volume totaling 1.5 million shares.
   Hilton Hotels dropped 1 1/8 to 51 3/4. Chairman Barron
Hilton told The Wall Street Journal he doesn't plan to put
the company up for sale again. Last month, the company's
board ended a 10-month auction by taking it off the market.
   Springs Industries fell 7/8 to 33 after estimating that
first-quarter earnings were about half the year-earlier level
of 86 cents a share.
   Mesa L.P. dropped 3/8 to 5 1/2. Moody's Investors Services
lowered its rating on the partnership's debt in response to
its decision against selling interests in some of its prime
properties for as much as $400 million.
   Crompton &amp; Knowles gained 1/4 to 33 5/8. The company
raised its quarterly dividend by about 35.5% to 21 cents a
share.
   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index dropped
0.16 to 359.52. Volume totaled 11,770,000 shares, compared
with 12,560,000 shares Monday. There were 281 issues
advancing, 287 declining and 246 were unchanged.
   B.A.T Industries, the most active Amex issue, dropped 3/8
to 12 1/2 as 690,400 shares were traded. British investor Sir
James Goldsmith received a major setback in his effort to
acquire the company as California regulators rejected his
proposed change in control of B.A.T's Farmers Group unit.
   Blount Inc. Class A dropped 1/2 to 12 5/8. The company
reported that first-quarter earnings from continuing
operations declined 24.3% from the year-earlier level.
</TEXT>
