<HL>
   Westcoast Energy Sets
   A Cogeneration Plant
   In British Columbia
</HL>
<DATE>
04/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA T.CU WE
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<LP>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia -- Westcoast Energy Inc. said
it plans to build with a partner a 106 million Canadian
dollar (US$91.3 million) cogeneration plant that will supply
electricity to B.C. Hydro, a provincially owned utility.
   The proposed McMahon Cogeneration Plant, which Westcoast
plans to build at Taylor in partnership with the CU Power
division of Canadian Utilities Ltd., would supply 105
megawatts of electricity to B.C. Hydro, beginning in October
1993.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Cogeneration is the simultaneous production of electricity
and steam, for use in industrial processes.
   B.C. Hydro said the contract with Westcoast and its
partner is valued at more than C$45 million annually, and
would run 20 years from the plant's start-up date. The
electric utility, Canada's third-biggest, said the new plant
is part of its push to encourage independent power production
in British Columbia, where consumption of electric power is
growing rapidly, along with the province's economy.
   Westcoast, a big natural-gas pipeline, utility, and oil
and gas production concern, said the new plant would be
located at the site of its existing McMahon gas processing
plant, in northeastern British Columbia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900411-0089
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900411-0089.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Cubic Corp. Engineer
   Acquitted on Charges
   In False-Records Case
</HL>
<DATE>
04/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<CO>
   CUB
</CO>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   SAN DIEGO -- A Cubic Corp. engineer was acquitted on
charges that he took part in falsifying records on a U.S.
Army mine-detector contract.
   Dennis B. Fink, 41 years old, was acquitted in a retrial
in federal court here, after a jury last year failed to vote
unanimously to acquit or convict him on 21 counts, including
conspiracy to defraud the government and submitting false
records. He was acquitted on two counts at that time.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   William B. Bauder, program manager for the mine-detector
program, was acquitted on all counts last August. The two men
were indicted by a federal grand jury in March 1988, after an
investigation that began in 1984.
   In 1988, Cubic, a high-technology concern, paid the
federal government about $7.3 million to settle claims that
it fraudulently tested the hand-held mine detectors it
refurbished for the Navy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900411-0088
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
