<HL>
   Notable &amp; Quotable
</HL>
<DATE>
04/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<LP>
   Henry Nau, senior staffer at the National Security Council
from 1981 to 1983, writing in the March/April issue of The
International Economy:
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Bretton Woods standards did not subordinate domestic
growth to international stability, as critics of U.S. dollar
policy began to argue in the 1960s; nor did they manipulate
international mechanisms such as exchange rates to
accommodate domestic expansion or inflation, as was done in
the 1970s. They recognized that domestic and international
stability and growth were directly interrelated. If domestic
prices began to diverge in the major countries, international
prices or exchange rates would also have to diverge. If
domestic economies became increasingly inflexible, countries
increasingly would have to make their balance of payments
adjustments through borrowing or through trade, exchange
rate, and capital market restrictions. There was no way to
have your cake and eat it, too. Domestic and international
policies depended upon one another: Domestic policies
couldn't succeed without international competition, and
international cooperation could not compensate for
undisciplined domestic policies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900411-0069
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900411-0069.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   S&amp;L Agency Still Will Pay
   Interest on Certain Debt
</HL>
<DATE>
04/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- In a policy pronouncement applauded by the
bond markets, the federal savings and loan bailout agency
said it would continue interest payments on certain S&amp;L debt
after the S&amp;Ls have been seized by the government.
   It continued to insist that it wasn't required to make the
payments, however.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Both Moody's Investors Service Inc. and Standard &amp; Poor's
Corp. said last month that they were reviewing about $20
billion in S&amp;L debt because of questions about the interest
payments. The questions arose when the government's
Resolution Trust Corp. said it believed that the S&amp;L
restructuring law gave it the authority to abandon interest
payments on certain S&amp;L debt even if the interest was backed
by a variety of collateral.
   The RTC announced last week that it intended to adopt a
policy of making the payments.
   Malcolm Dorris, partner with Dechert Price &amp; Rhoads,
outside counsel to Standard &amp; Poor's, said the rating agency
was pleased with the statement. "From a rating perspective,
it eliminates the concern," he said.
   Frances Bermanzohn, general counsel to the Public
Securities Association, called the RTC policy "a vindication
for bondholders. It will restore calm to markets and investor
confidence in the RTC."
</TEXT>
