<HL>
   Taiwan to Open Reserves
</HL>
<DATE>
04/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
BANKS (BNK)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan -- The Central Bank announced that it will
appropriate a part of Taiwan's foreign exchange reserves to
refinance Taiwanese businesses that plan to invest or seek
mergers and acquisitions overseas.
   The move is aimed at using Taiwan's approximately $73
billion in local foreign exchange reserves to expand Taiwan's
economic base and stimulate further development, Yu Chen, the
Central Bank's deputy governor, said at a news conference. He
said the move might trigger short-term capital outflow, but
in the longer term, earnings from overseas investment are
likely to extend Taiwan's economic strength.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Those eligible for the loans include companies involved in
natural resource development, high technology, anti-pollution
technology, and management training, he said. The Bank of
Communications, Export-Import Bank of the Republic of China,
International Commercial Bank of China and the China
Development Corp. are the four banks designated to issue the
loans.
</TEXT>
