</DOCID>
<HL>
   Who's News:
   Herman Miller Inc.'s
   Chief of Operations,
   President Quits Posts
</HL>
<DATE>
04/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9
</SO>
<CO>
   MLHR WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   ZEELAND, Mich. -- Herman Miller Inc. said its president
and chief operating officer, Edward R. Simon Jr., is
resigning, effective June 1, and that another top official is
taking early retirement. No successor was named for either
man.
   Mr. Simon's resignation came two years after the furniture
maker appointed Richard H. Ruch as its chief executive
officer, putting him above Mr. Simon, who has been president
since 1986.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In a statement, Mr. Simon, 52 years old, said "the
direction of the corporation is best served by reducing
duplication and overlapping responsibilities in management. .
. . I recognize that my resignation will provide {Ruch} with
an opportunity for further alignment of the organization,
eliminate confusion and provide a clearer direction for the
company."
   Mr. Simon wasn't available for comment and the company
didn't offer any further details beyond the statement other
than to say that its financial position is solid and neither
the resignation nor the early retirement was forced.
   Herman Miller also said that David L. Armstrong, its
senior vice president for sales and marketing, is taking
early retirement but didn't specify when. Mr. Armstrong is 54
and has been with Herman Miller 11 years, the company said.
   The effect of the two officers leaving is difficult to
assess. Mr. Simon worked for Herman Miller for some 20 years,
during which he helped establish an internal data processing
and information system for the company, led a financial
turnaround at a subsidiary, and helped set up a global
distribution network. Mr. Armstrong directed the introduction
of several new products and served as executive vice
president of Herman Miller Research Corp.
   Herman Miller stock closed yesterday at $19 a share, down
25 cents in national over-the-counter trading.
   In the 1970s and early 1980s, Herman Miller stock was a
highflier, riding the crest of a rapidly growing market for
office furniture. Then the market for office furniture
slowed, causing a "shock" in Herman Miller's earnings and
sales growth, said Wallace W. Epperson, an analyst with Wheat
First Securities in Richmond, Va.
   For the third quarter ended March 3, Herman Miller earned
$11.5 million, or 47 cents a share, on sales of $200.7
million. In the year-earlier quarter, net income totaled
$10.9 million, or 45 cents a share, on sales of $192.6
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900411-0014
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900411-0014.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News:
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
04/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   THE THRIFT BAILOUT AGENCY flopped in its second attempt to
sell 40-year bonds, a sign that investors aren't ready for
bonds that have extra-long maturities. The $3.5 billion
auction of so-called "bailout bonds" went poorly despite a
higher-than-expected average yield of 8.89%.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Treasury-bond prices tumbled in reaction to the S&amp;L bond
auction. Stocks edged higher, while the dollar fell against
the mark and yen.
   ---
   William Farley plans to surrender majority ownership of
West Point-Pepperell because he is unable to pay for the
$1.56 billion acquisition. The move follows last year's
bitter takeover battle with the textile giant.
   ---
   Lockheed's board easily won its proxy battle against
Dallas investor Harold Simmons. But a slate of Simmons-backed
initiatives also was approved, signaling holders want more
say in the defense firm's revival.
   ---
   The Big Three auto makers are expected to post a 70% drop
in first-quarter earnings, reflecting efforts to clear
bloated inventories. The strategy included a 26.5% reduction
in quarterly production and sales incentives averaging $1,000
a vehicle.
   ---
   Merrill Lynch has tightened its grip on how it credits
investors' securities proceeds, which could save the firm
millions of dollars that had gone to clients. Merrill brokers
are complaining about the move, though it is practiced by
other big brokerages.
   ---
   Bell Atlantic said its Bell of Pennsylvania phone unit
agreed to pay $42 million to settle charges it used
"deceptive techniques" to sell customers more services than
they wanted.
   ---
   Eastern Airlines' unsecured creditors asked a bankruptcy
court to remove the carrier's management and appoint a
trustee to run the troubled Texas Air subsidiary.
   ---
   Credit Suisse's parent is discussing an alliance with Bank
Leu, paving the way for a long-awaited consolidation of the
Swiss banking market.
   ---
   Two Mitsubishi Group firms plan to reunite despite
expected criticism that they are trying to re-establish their
prewar monopoly in Japan.
   ---
   OPEC is growing nervous about the continued slide in oil
prices. But the group is unlikely to take any action before
late May, when it holds its regular midyear conference.
   ---
   Time Warner's long-term public debt was placed on S&amp;P's
CreditWatch with negative implications due to its financing
pact with Pathe.
   ---
   Massachusetts announced steps to help firms obtain loans
amid growing concern that a credit crunch may be worsening
the state's economic woes.
   ---
   Motorola posted a modest 3.3% in first-quarter earnings,
but signs that its computer-chip business is rebounding sent
its stock higher.
   ---
   Westinghouse Electric reported that first-quarter earnings
rose 11%, though revenue dropped slightly.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 136,020,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2731.08, up 9.01; transportation 1176.39, up 5.34; utilities
213.03, off 1.07.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3327.03, off
10.65.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.59, up 0.70; spot
index 134.90, up 0.53.
   Dollar: 157.60 yen, off 0.63; 1.6755 marks, off 0.0180.
</TEXT>
