<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
04/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   GORBACHEV RAISED the possibility of imposing direct rule
over Lithuania.
   As the president of the breakaway Baltic republic blamed
"ultra-rightist" forces for Moscow's threat to use
unspecified political and economic measures against
Lithuania, the Soviet leader warned that he might impose
direct presidential rule in the event of "civilian conflict
or confrontation." Such a step could include martial law and
dissolving the republic's legislature. Gorbachev, who noted
that Lithuania's independence bid could be costly to
international peace, also said that the Kremlin was still
striving to find a political solution to the situation.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   With opposition expected to a planned economic package,
Gorbachev said his advisory council would meet Saturday to
discuss speeding market changes.
   ---
   Palestinian extremists in Beirut freed a French woman, a
Belgian man and their young daughter after holding them
hostage for more than two years. The three were taken to
Paris following their release by a Libyan-backed group headed
by Abu Nidal. The move came a month after France returned
three jet fighters to Gadhafi.
   ---
   Walesa confirmed that he would run for Poland's presidency
in the country's next elections, according to the state-owned
PAP news agency. A top aide to the Solidarity founder said
Walesa was prepared to force President Jaruzelski to resign
because of the slow pace of political and economic change,
Reuters news agency reported.
   ---
   NASA scrubbed the launch of the space shuttle Discovery
and said it could be as long as two weeks before a new
attempt to carry the $1.5 billion Hubble Space Telescope into
orbit. Space agency officials at Cape Canaveral in Florida
said the countdown was halted by a faulty power unit in the
spacecraft's steering system.
   ---
   Bush said there is "an awful lot to be done" to resolve
U.S.-Soviet arms-control differences before next month's
superpower summit. The president, in Canada for a meeting
with Prime Minister Mulroney, also said that "should things
deteriorate in Lithuania, it would be extraordinarily
difficult" for U.S.-Soviet ties to improve quickly.
   ---
   Federal safety officials concluded that lapses by Boeing
Co., United Airlines and the FAA contributed to the February
1989 failure of a cargo door on a jetliner over the Pacific
Ocean. The resulting decompression caused several feet of
cabin floor to collapse, sending nine passengers to their
deaths.
   ---
   East German legislators haggled over unfilled cabinet
posts, delaying an agreement on East Europe's first freely
elected coalition. The last-minute wrangling reportedly
centered on the post of economic minister, who would play a
crucial role in the nation's change to a free-market system
and in its reunification with West Germany.
   ---
   Greece's Mitsotakis was designated premier and asked by
the president to form a new government. The conservative
leader, whose New Democracy party won 150 seats in the
300-member legislature in Sunday's nationwide elections,
secured the backing of a centrist deputy for a majority.
   ---
   Health researchers have discovered new evidence linking
stress on the job to high blood pressure. The study found
that men who hold jobs with demands over which they have
little control are more likely to have high blood pressure
and to sustain physical changes to the heart than men who
don't face such strains.
   ---
   India's prime minister said the country should be
"psychologically prepared" for an armed conflict with
Pakistan over the disputed Kashmir valley. Singh made his
remarks in New Delhi's Parliament after Moslem secessionists
in the valley killed a Hindu industrialist held since Friday.
   ---
   Western travelers in Beijing said two envoys sent last
week to calm Islamic unrest in China's remote northwest were
killed. Security forces reportedly killed about 50 people in
subsequent riots. Regional officials have declined to comment
on the reports.
   ---
   The Census Bureau reported that the number of men in the
U.S. grew faster than the population of women in the 1980s,
something that hasn't happened since the first decade of the
century. Death rates for men declined more rapidly than for
women, but the report showed that women continue to outnumber
men in the country.
   ---
   Mongolia's Communist Party opened a meeting in Ulan Bator
with an appeal for political and economic restructuring in an
attempt to maintain its 70-year-old grip on power amid
growing pro-democracy demands. The three-day meeting comes
ahead of planned multiparty elections.
   ---
   Mandela will lead an 11-member African National Congress
delegation in talks next month with the government on
black-white power sharing. Following the May 2-4 discussions,
the black nationalist leader will embark on a series of
foreign trips, including stops in the U.S. and the Soviet
Union.
</TEXT>
